Show HN: Argilla and AutoTrain – Train custom NLP models without code
text:
Hi there!

I'm Daniel, co-founder of Argilla, an open-source data labeling platform for NLP. We've recently launched two integrations with the Hugging Face Hub to (1) deploy your own data labeling instance on the Hub, and (2) launch AutoTrain jobs for text classification, NER, and text generation.

You can try the whole workflow for free (i.e., Argilla Space can be deployed on free Hub instances, and AutoTrain is free up to 3000 examples

As we start building more integrations to simplify going from your own data to a trained model we'd love to get your feedback!

Ask HN: Are universities places of free-thinking and growth?
text:
I’m not as interested in university for the courses, but more so for a social experience that would expose me to people studying a wide range of subjects with an eye to improve the way of the world.

Was it ever like this? Or am I being idealistic?

I feel like our culture as a whole is a little more strapped for cash, hence needing to work often, and therefore relaxing and thinking less. There seems to be more censorship, and the universities themselves are more corporate rather than truly offering nurturing environments for student growth and wellbeing.

Is the era of going to university for more than just a degree over?

Ask HN: Google voice is great, why is it free?
text:
I've used Google Voice at least 10 years, probably spent hundreds of hours in calls and many tens or hundreds of hours in Hangouts for voice and screen sharing (mainly work, though Hangouts went away) before Teams or Zoom became popular.

I don't get how they could offer Google Voice for so long for free. I put $10 in my account back when I signed up for my number way back then and not a cent has ever been charged by Google, which is amazing but odd.

Ask HN: Should the Department of Justice be investigating Nvidia's monopoly?
text:
GPU prices remain crazy.

Initially the prices went up due to crypto mining.

But when the newest generation of GPUs came out, crypto mining had finished being viable, and yet prices remain eye wateringly high.

The suggestions is that Nvidia and AMD are doing this deliberately.

Nvidia pretty much owns the GPU market.

AMD has competitive cards, but seems unwilling to compete.

Intel unable to develop a card that competes anywhere except the lowest end.

So I wondered, is the monopolistic / anti competitive illegal activity in any of this?

Should the Department of Justice be investigating the GPU market?
